<p Class="lead"><strong>Borders and shading are formatting tools that are used to highlight or
emphasize text and information in a document or to make the document more
attractive and appealing.</strong><p class="lead"> 


<p>Borders and shading can be used together or separately throughout a document.</p>

<p><strong>Borders</strong> are decorative elements that go around a word, a section of text or even a whole page</p>

<p><strong>Shading</strong> is a decorative element that highlights with color a word, a section of text or paragraph.</p>

<p>You can place a border and/or shading around text and the selections you
make in the <strong>Borders and Shading Option Box</strong> will determine how the border is placed. If you apply the border or shading to the <strong>text</strong>, it wraps the border just around the text. If you apply the border or shading to the <strong>paragraph</strong>, it extends to the margin.</p>

<p>Below are examples of the differences:</p>

<img class="img-wrap style1" src="images/wordprocessing/bordershadingexample.jpg" alt="">


<p>Notice that in the first example, the border is tight around the text. In
the second example, the border extends to the margin. The same holds true for
shading.</p>

<p>Select the text you want to put a border around or shade first!</p>


<p>Accessing Borders and Shading Options Box is different depending on your version, but the <strong>Border Options</strong> box is the same for all versions.</p>


